      "side": 1,
      "message": "In this case one options is to implement the sort.Interface, like this\n\ntype resultRecLessFn func(r *resultRecSlice, i, j int) bool\ntype resultRecSlice struct {\n\tlessFn resultRecLessFn\n\tdata   []*ResultRec\n}\n\nfunc newResultRecSlice(data []*ResultRec, lessFn resultRecLessFn) *resultRecSlice {\n\treturn \u0026resultRecSlice{lessFn: lessFn, data: data}\n}\n\nfunc (r *resultRecSlice) Len() int           { return len(r.data) }\nfunc (r *resultRecSlice) Less(i, j int) bool { return r.lessFn(c, i, j) }\nfunc (r *resultRecSlice) Swap(i, j int)      { r.data[i], r.data[j] \u003d r.data[j], r.data[i] }\n\nThis has the advantage that you can then wrap around the slice you want to sort and use sort.Reverse to deal with the asc/desc issue. i.e. \n\nsortSlice :\u003d sort.Interface(newResultRecSlice(results, func(r  *resultRecSlice, i, j int) bool {\n                 ...\n             }))\n\nif sortOrder \u003d\u003d DESC {\n    sortSlice \u003d sort.Reverse(sortSlice)\n}\nsort.Sort(sortSlice)\n\n\nThe switch statemtent can then be reduced to finding the right version of he resultRecLessFn.\nJust a suggestion.",
